\begin_layout Subsection
Rock-Paper-Scissors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The game is symmetrical and no pure strategy NE exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Peope are irrational by their nature, and biased.
 A winner will tend to play the same hand again and a loser will tend to
 change its hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hot-hand fallacy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: in basketball, players are perceived to have a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot hand
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 during a game (if they managed to score 2-3 in a row it gives an impression
 that the ball should be passed to them).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People's intuition is that the probability to score after a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

throw
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is higher then the unconditional probability:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Pr(H|H)>Pr(H)>P(H|M)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analyzing data from real games, the conclusion is that the probability tis
 exactly the same, thus there is no such thing as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot hand
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Case of Kitty Genovese
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A woman was murdered in New York City.
 38 neighbors witnessed it, but no one called the police.
 A model for this situation is a game with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 players, a personal cost of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fighting the dragon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is 1 and the personal utility if someone else does it is 
\begin_inset Formula $x>1$
\end_inset

.
 With pure strategy NE are when a single player 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fights
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but it is implausible without prior coordination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a mixed-strategy BE: each player fights with some probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, which makes them 
\series bold
indifferent
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The payoff in case of fighting is 
\begin_inset Formula $x-1$
\end_inset

, and in case of not fighting is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\cdot(1-(1-p)^{n-1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indifference requires:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x-1=x\cdot(1-(1-p)^{n-1})\Rightarrow p=1-\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)^{\frac{1}{n-1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chances that 
\series bold
someone
\series default
 will call the police are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)^{\frac{n}{n-1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 and converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

