\begin_layout Subsection
Existence of NE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What makes some predictions more plausible than others? For a prediction
 to be 
\series bold
good
\series default
, it has to exist for every game.
 It can be shown that evey finite game has a NE equilibrium (possibly a
 mixed one).
 The proof is made using the Kakutani's fixed point theorem , applied to
 the best response function of each player.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extensive-Form Games
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative way to describe games is by using a tree structure.
 The game is represented by a tree, a set of players, map of the nodes to
 players who move on them and a map of paths to their payoffs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such form is usually easier than strategic-form game, and the additional
 information in the tree structure helps selecting among the different NE.
\end_layout

