\begin_layout Subsection
Stackelberg Competition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 2 firms need to choose quantities with production costs equal zero
 and demand 
\begin_inset Formula $P(q_{1},q_{2})=1-q_{1}-q_{2}$
\end_inset

, and firm 1 plays first.
 Attempting to maximize its utility, the first firm would choose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{1}^{*}=\frac{1}{2}
\]

\end_inset

 as the second firm will choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-q_{1}}{2}$
\end_inset

 (maximizing the utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}(1-q_{1}-q_{2})$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Take-it-or-leave-it
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two players divide $4 in integer units, with the first one proposing a division
 and the second one accepting or rejecting it (for both).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Player 1 expects player 2 to accept any division, thus it will give player
 2 the lowest possible amount.
 In case 0 can be chosen - there are 2 possible outcomes (player 2 is indifferen
t).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the game is continuous, player 2 will accept any positive offer and be
 indifferent with an offer of zero, which is considered as the solution
 in such case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now a situation when the players alternate in making offers, with
 each period discounted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 (e.g a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

melting ice-cream
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and the opportunity can disappeat with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\delta$
\end_inset

.
 The person who makes the offer will win, in the second round.
\end_layout

